From: dminer@nyx10.cs.du.edu (Dan Miner)
Subject: Re: Linux Kernel Buffer questions...
Date: Mon, 22 Nov 93 14:25:27 GMT

[lots of deleted stuff]
>just another question:
>i had to copy parts of a cd to tape.
>when i started tar from the cd to the tape after a while the buffers
>wher 16 mb size and they gave *no* better performance. the tape begun to
>stream and stoped, begun to stream and stoped, ..., it took more than 5 
>hours to write 248 mb to tape. the 16 mb buffer werenot filed with a bigger 
>amount of data from the cd-rom and then transferedto tape. the large buffer 
>was completely useless... .now i wonder if there are more circumstances 
>where such a large bufferis useless and a better strategy would have been 
>better (i don't meanany special options to tar..:-) )? 

>e-mail: A.Schroeter@DKFZ-Heidelberg.de

Here is how I understand streaming tape drives.

Every controller/drive has X memory for a buffer.  Now, if this buffer
is filled, the controller sends a "STOP!" and tells you AFTER all the
data is written to start again.  Once the data is written, the controller 
stops the drive itself waits Y time (milliseconds I believe) and starts to
rewind the tape back for a running start for the next read/write command.
[Note: this happens only (usually) if no commands are executed in those
Y time periods].

As you can guess, THIS IS bad for performance.  It doesn't matter HOW
big your buffer is (in the computer).  Your software and the controller
MUST sync themselves so this "back tracking the heads" doesn't
happen very offen.  I have an algorithm for this very thing floating
around my roon [Lord, help us find it :)].  I believe you can find it
in the "Software: Experiences and Practices", July '93.

Hope this helps,
Dan

P.S.  If you can convince tar how to sync like this, I'd be interesed in
knowing.  (Note: I do not have a tape backup system so I can't write
the software to do this..... :)
--
Dan Miner                                       dminer@nyx.cs.du.edu

Future student                                  Linux: try it, you'll like.
"Your program is encoded in pi."                I started with a 64

