From: wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de (Kai Petzke)
Subject: Re: TAMU X INSTALL
Date: 22 Nov 1993 14:36:22 GMT

In <c878109.753973175@id.dth.dk> c878109@idcad7.uucp (Michael Cederberg) writes:

>One thing that I would like so see, is a MSDOZE program that could query my
>card about it's current mode. This way, I'll be able to use the parameters
>in BIOS which shouldn't burn my card. I realize that not all XFree86 users
>use MSDOS, but nearly everybody has the ability to boot from an MSDOS-floppy.

Does windoze boot from a floppy, too?  You want to query your card
about its graphics mode settings, and these can only be achieved
by switching it into that mode.  For example, my ET4000 card came
with a driver for windows.  Installing it was lots of work.  Without
installing it, windows just gets you standard EGA, 640x480 and 16
colours or something like that.

But DOS supports a semi-standard interrupt to switch VGA modes.
Semi-standard, because not all cards support all modes.  We could
write a small DOS executable, which allows to switch the modes,
and then call a "safe registers" function when you like a certain
mode.

This register values could then be printed out in a format suitable
for including into the Xconfig file.
--
Kai
wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de
Advertisement by Microsoft in a well-known German magazine:
        If you don't like our programmes, than make your own ones.
However, they expect you to use Microsoft products for this -:)

