Crossposted-To: comp.windows.x,comp.windows.x.i386unix,comp.windows.x.motif,gnu.misc.discuss,comp.sources.d
From: mkl@rob.cs.tu-bs.de (Mario Klebsch DG1AM)
Subject: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Date: Mon, 22 Nov 1993 16:12:05 GMT

mjr@syl.dl.nec.com (Matt Ranney) writes:
>"too large" for what?  He said they were "too large to be useful,"
>which is obviously incorrect because there are thousands of people out
>there like me who get use out of it.  You must get use out of it too,
>otherwise why would you have it on your disk?  Plus, it's a lousy 2
>megs.  Big deal.  Once you get a bunch of images going, it can easily
>take up an additional 2 megs or more.  The gcc dir on my system is
>around 12 megs, and it's probably about that much on your system too,
>assuming it wasn't "too large" for you.

But please don't forget that these staticaly linked executables do
not only need more space on disk, but also need more virtual memory
when executiing. And this means a lot more swapping, if the user does
not upgrade main memory capacity. That is going to be especialy a
Problem e.g. on Suns with 16 MByte running Solaris 2.x on on 4-8 MByte
Linux systems.
If you have a graphic library which is shared, you can easily add features,
increasing the size of this library. All the code is shared between all
processes using this library. This makes the "look and feel" of all
applications hopefully better and consistant. But if you have to think
of memory, you will double check every feature before including it. Let's
take the open look text editing widget as an example: This widget has a
popup menu on the right mouse button with all the function of a text
editor (load, save, cut, paste, find, ...). You will find these functions
in every application using this widget. So, if you have a find & replce
dialog box in a text editor, you can, for example, load the replacement
string from a file, you prepared before. A nice feature, if you need it,
but you normaly would not implement this feature.
So I would prefer using one probably large, but shared, library
implementing the widget set instead of using libraries reduced to the
absolute needs of the application. The user, who is familliar with the
"look and feel" of the widget set will thank you.

Mario

-- 
Mario Klebsch, DG1AM, mkl@rob.cs.tu-bs.de               (49) 531 / 391 - 7457
Institut fuer Robotik und Prozessinformatik der TU Braunschweig
